<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Committees of the Board of Directors</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Audit Committee.</B> We have a standing Audit Committee. &nbsp;Mr. Herbert B. Soroca serves as the Chairman and
sole member of the Audit Committee. &nbsp;He qualifies as an audit committee financial expert as defined in Item 407(d)(5) of Regulation S-k promulgated
under the Exchange Act. &nbsp;The Audit Committee currently does not operate in accordance with a written charter, but intends to adopt one prior to the Company&#146;s
 next annual stockholders&#8217; meeting.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The Audit Committee is appointed by the Board to assist the Board with oversight of (i) the integrity of the
financial statements of the Company, (ii) the Company&#8217;s compliance with legal and regulatory requirements, (iii) the independence and
qualifications of the Company&#8217;s external auditors, and (iv) the performance of the Company&#8217;s internal audit function and external auditors.
&nbsp;It is the Audit Committee&#8217;s responsibility to retain or terminate the Company&#8217;s independent registered public accountants, who audit
the Company&#8217;s financial statements. &nbsp;As part of its activities, the Audit Committee meets with the Company&#8217;s independent registered
public accountants at least annually to review the scope and results of the annual audit and quarterly to discuss the review of the quarterly financial results. &nbsp;In addition, the Audit Committee receives and considers the independent registered public
accountants&#8217; comments and recommendations as to internal controls, accounting staff, management performance and auditing procedures.</P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center>18</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>


<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>ITEM&nbsp;10.<I>&nbsp;&nbsp;Directors, Executive Officers and Corporate Governance (continued)</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Nominating Committee.</B> The board of directors has determined that, due to its current size, formation of a
separate nominating committee would not be an efficient use of resources. &nbsp;The board intends to form a Nominating Committee in the future.
&nbsp;All directors, currently participate in consideration of director nominees. &nbsp;The board will consider suggestions from stockholders for names
of possible future nominees delivered in writing and received one hundred and twenty (120) days in advance of our Annual Meeting of Stockholders.
&nbsp;Such recommendation should provide all information relating to such person that the stockholder desires to nominate that is required to be
disclosed in solicitation of proxies pursuant to Regulation 14A under the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Communications with Board Members</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>We have not adopted a formal process by which stockholders may communicate with the board of directors. Stockholders
may contact our Chief Executive Officer at eric@psicoupons.com.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Section 16(a) Beneficial Ownership Reporting Compliance</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Section 16(a) of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended, requires that our directors and executive officers
and persons who beneficially own more than 10% of our common stock (referred to herein as the &#8220;reporting persons&#8221;) file with the SEC various
reports as to their ownership of and activities relating to our common stock. Such reporting persons are required by SEC regulations to furnish us with
copies of all Section 16(a) reports they file. Messrs. Kash, Soroca and Tammaro have not filed their Form&nbsp;3s reporting their
appointments as Officers of the Company and issuances of equity securities made by the Company to them as compensation for services, which they intend to file in the
second quarter of fiscal 2012.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><B>Code of Ethics</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Due to size and limited resources of the Company, we have not adopted a formal Code of Ethics, however the Board
closely reviews all transactions that the Company is involved in. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><I>Employment Agreements with Our Named Executive Officers</I></P>
<P style="margin-top:5.533px; margin-bottom:5.533px" align=justify>Since November 10, 2008, we have had an employment contract in place with Eric L.
Kash, Chief Executive Officer and Chief Financial Officer. In consideration of his furnished services, Mr. Kash is entitled to receive $10,000 per month
as base salary compensation and additional equity compensation as described below, which was deferred for fiscal 2009, 2010 and 2011. However, in
October&nbsp;2011, Mr. Kash received in lieu of deferred salary for the three year period ended a warrant, to purchase 36,000,000 shares of the
Company&#8217;s common stock at an exercise price of $.001 per share.</P>
<P style="margin-top:5.533px; margin-bottom:5.533px" align=justify>In the event of Mr. Kash&#8217;s resignation or termination for cause, we owe no
further financial liability to Mr. Kash, other than with respect to accrued, unpaid salary and other compensation earned prior to termination. In the
event of a termination without cause, Mr. Kash is entitled to receive the base salary he is owed through the five-year contract term, a maximum of
$600,000.</P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Times" align=justify><B>Director Compensation </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>We do not separately compensate employee directors for their position as director. <FONT
style="font-family:Times">We compensate our non-employee directors with stock options, which we believe aligns director compensation directly with our
long-term performance. Stock options are granted to non-employee directors upon election or appointment, as the case may be, and on an annual basis.
</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Within 120 days of election, each director shall receive a grant for 500,000 shares for his services provided as a director and an
additional 333,000 shares as head of a committee of the Board of Directors. </P>

<P style="margin:0px"><B>ITEM&nbsp;11.<I>&nbsp;&nbsp;Executive Compensation (continued)</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Compensation Committee Interlocks and Insider Participation</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The Board of Directors has determined that, due to its current size, formation of a separate compensation committee
would not be an efficient use of resources.&nbsp;&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>ITEM&nbsp;12.<I>&nbsp;&nbsp;Security Ownership of Certain Beneficial Owners and Management</I></B> <B><I>and
Related Stockholder Matters.</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><B>Equity Compensation Plans</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>In October 2011, we adopted, subject to stockholder approval, the 2011 Non-Qualified Stock Option Plan (the
&#8220;Plan&#8221;). &nbsp;Under the terms of the Plan, the purchase price of the shares subject to each option grant will not be less than the fair
market value at the date of grant. &nbsp;The date of exercise may be determined at the time of grant by our Board, but may not exceed five years.
&nbsp;During the fiscal year ended October&nbsp;31, 2011, no options were granted under the Plan. &nbsp;As of October 31, 2011, 20,000,000 shares remain
available for issuance under the Plan.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The Plan is intended to serve as an additional incentive to all employees and key individuals to devote themselves
to our future success by providing them with an opportunity to increase their proprietary interest through the receipt of options to purchase our common
stock.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The Board determines and designates those individuals who are to be granted stock options under the Plan and the
number of shares to be subject to such options and, as hereinafter described, the nature and terms of the options to be granted. &nbsp;The Board shall
also, subject to the express provisions of the Plan, have authority to interpret the Plan and to prescribe, amend, and rescind the rules and regulations
relating to the Plan.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Unless otherwise noted in an individual option agreement or other agreement governing an award under the Plan, any
unvested stock options held by an employee at the time of his termination of service from us for any reason will be forfeited.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><B>Security Ownership of Certain Beneficial Owners and Management</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The following table sets forth certain information as of the date hereof with respect to the beneficial ownership of
the outstanding shares of Common Stock by (i) each of the directors and director nominee; (ii) each of our named executive officers listed in the
summary compensation table; and (iii) our current officers and directors (and&nbsp;nominee) as a group.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>As used in the table below, the term &#8220;beneficial ownership&#8221; means the sole or shared power to vote or
direct the voting, or to dispose or direct the disposition, of any security. &nbsp;A person is deemed as of any date to have beneficial ownership of any
security that such person has a right to acquire within 60 days after such date. &nbsp;Except as otherwise indicated, the stockholders listed below have
sole voting and investment powers with respect to the shares indicated. Accordingly, the number of shares and percentage set forth opposite each stockholder&#146;s name in the
table include the shares of Common Stock issuable upon exercise, conversion or exchange of certain derivative securities beneficially owned by such person, both with respect to the number of shares of Common Stock deemed to be beneficially
owned and the adjusted percentage of outstanding Common Stock resulting from such rights.





</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" STYLE="font-size: 10pt"><TR height=0 style="font-size:0"><TD width=187.2></TD><TD width=162></TD><TD width=67.733></TD>

extension at the option of the holders of a majority in principal amount of the Senior Notes), are convertible into shares of the Company&#8217;s
Series&nbsp;A Preferred Stock (&#8220;Preferred Stock&#8221;) at a rate of one share of Preferred Stock for each $25,000 of Senior Notes. Each
share of Preferred Stock is convertible into 1,250,000 shares of the Issuer&#8217;s Common Stock, subject to certain adjustments. The Warrants are
exercisable until October&nbsp;24, 2016 at a price of $.04 per share (subject to certain adjustments) and entitle the holder to purchase 1,250,000
shares of the Company&#8217;s Common Stock for each $25,000 of principal amount of Senior Notes.</P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>ITEM&nbsp;13.<I>&nbsp;&nbsp;Certain Relationships, Related Transactions, and Director

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Director Independence</B>.</P>
<P style="margin-top:5.533px; margin-bottom:5.533px; font-family:Times" align=justify>During the fiscal year ended October 31, 2011, Eric L. Kash,
Herbert Soroca, James Tammaro, and Joseph Heller served as members of our Board of Directors. Each of the directors, except for Mr. Kash, are
&#8220;independent&#8221; as defined in Rule&nbsp;4200(a)(15) of the NASDAQ Marketplace Rules.<A NAME="Item14"></A></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>ITEM&nbsp;14.<I>&nbsp;&nbsp;Principal Accounting Fees and Services</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Audit Fees</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px">The aggregate fees billed for the fiscal year that ended on October 31, 2011 for professional services rendered by the independent
auditor for the audit of our annual financial statements and review of financial statements included in our Form 10-Q, or services that are normally
provided by the accountant in connection with the statutory and regulatory filings or engagements for such fiscal year, amount to approximately $32,600.
</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The aggregate fees billed for the fiscal year that ended on October 31, 2010 for professional services rendered by
the independent auditor for the audit of our annual financial statements and review of financial statements included in our Form 10-Q, or services that
are normally provided by the accountant in connection with the statutory and regulatory filings or engagements for such fiscal year, amount to
approximately $25,000.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>For the fiscal years ended on October 31, 2011 and 2010, there were no fees billed for assurance and related
services by the independent auditor that are reasonably related to the performance of the audit or review of our financial statements and are not
reported under Item 9(e) (1) of Schedule 14A.</P>

products or services provided by the independent auditor other than the services reported in the three preceding paragraphs.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><B>Audit Committee Pre-Approval Policies and Procedures</B>&nbsp;&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px">The Audit Committee has established a policy to pre-approve all audit and permissible non-audit services provided by our
independent registered public accounting firm. All of the services provided during fiscal year 2010 were pre-approved.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>During the approval process, the Audit Committee considered the impact of the types of services and the related fees
on the independence of the independent registered public accounting firm. The services and fees were deemed compatible with the maintenance of that
firm&#8217;s independence, including compliance with rules and regulations of the SEC. Throughout the year, the Audit Committee will review any
revisions to the estimates of audit fees initially estimated for the engagement.</P>

<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:0px" align=center>F-1</P>



<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>

<!-- *************************************************************************** -->
<!-- MARKER PAGE="sheet: 3; page: 3" -->
<HR SIZE=5 COLOR=GRAY NOSHADE>
<PAGE>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-family:Times" align=center><B><U>REPORT OF INDEPENDENT REGISTERED PUBLIC ACCOUNTING FIRM</U></B>
</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>To the Board of Directors and Stockholders of Coupon Express, Inc.:</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>I have audited the accompanying balance sheets of Coupon Express, Inc. (the &#8220;Company&#8221;) as of October 31,
2011 and 2010 and the related statements of operations, stockholders&#8217; deficit, and cash flows for the years then ended. These financial statements
are the responsibility of the Company&#8217;s management. My responsibility is to express an opinion on these financial statements based on my audits.
</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>I conducted my audits in accordance with the standards of the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (United
States). Those standards require that I plan and perform the audit to obtain reasonable assurance about whether the financial statements are free of
material misstatement. The Company is not required to have, nor was I engaged to perform, an audit of its internal control over financial reporting. My
audits included consideration of internal control over financial reporting as a basis for designing audit procedures that are appropriate in the
circumstances, but not for the purpose of expressing an opinion on the effectiveness of the Company&#8217;s internal control over financial reporting.
Accordingly, I express no such opinion. An audit includes examining, on a test basis, evidence supporting the amounts and disclosures in the financial
statements, assessing the accounting principles used and significant estimates made by management, as well as evaluating the overall financial statement
presentation. I believe that my audits provide a reasonable basis for my opinion.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>In my opinion, the financial statements referred to above present fairly, in all material respects, the financial
position of Coupon Express, Inc. as of October 31, 2011 and 2010, and the results of its operations and its cash flows for the years then ended in
conformity with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The accompanying financial statements have been prepared assuming that the Company will continue as a going concern.
&nbsp;As discussed in Note 1 to the financial statements, the Company has incurred significant recurring losses. The realization of a major portion of
its assets is dependent upon its ability to meet future financing needs and success of its future operations. These factors raise substantial doubt
about the Company&#8217;s ability to continue as a going concern. &nbsp;The financial statements do not include any adjustments that might result from
the outcome of this uncertainty.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>/s/ Patrick Rodgers, CPA, PA&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Orlando, Florida</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>January 16, 2012</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>




<P style="margin:0px" align=center><B>COUPON EXPRESS, INC.</B></P>
<P style="margin-top:6.667px; margin-bottom:0px" align=center><B>NOTES&nbsp;TO FINANCIAL STATEMENTS</B></P>
<P style="margin-top:6.667px; margin-bottom:0px" align=center><B>FOR THE YEARS ENDED OCTOBER 31, 2011 AND 2010</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px"><B>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;Organization and Going Concern</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><I>Organization</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Coupon Express, Inc. (&#8220;CE&#8221; or the &#8220;Company&#8221;) was organized under the laws of Nevada in June,
1991. CE provides innovative interactive customer communications systems and applications that support targeted marketing programs with unique
point-of-purchase (POP) services and information that serve shoppers and distributors while building loyalty and revenue for the Company&#8217;s primary
clients. Through our proprietary kiosks, we provide in-store customized couponing, in multiple languages, for immediate impact in regional, independent
retailers in the grocery and convenience store industries, enabling retailers to quickly determine ideal price-points for new products and mitigate
losses from hard-to-sell items. Working with Midax, Inc., a systems integrator for the independent grocery and convenience store industries and its
software applications, marketing services and existing customer base, we provide a seamless transaction for issuing, redeeming and reporting coupons, as
well as creating a state-of-the-art loyalty program and shopping list service.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><I>Going Concern</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Our financial statements have been prepared on the assumption that we will continue as a going concern, which
contemplates the continuation of operations, the realization of assets and the liquidation of liabilities in the ordinary course of business, and do not
reflect any adjustments that might result from our ability to being unable to continue as a going concern. &nbsp;At October 31, 2011, we had total
assets of $1,268,386 and liabilities of $2,177,174. Our management is aware that we need to raise additional capital not only to meet our financial
obligations, but also to expand our business. &nbsp;These factors cumulatively indicate that there is substantial doubt about our ability to continue as
a going concern. &nbsp;The accompanying financial statements do not include any adjustments that might be necessary should we be unable to continue as a
going concern.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Summary of Significant Accounting Policies</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><I>Accounting Principles</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><I>&nbsp;&nbsp;</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The financial statements and accompanying notes are prepared in accordance with accounting principles generally
accepted in the United States.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><I>Cash and Cash Equivalents</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>We consider all highly liquid interest-earning investments with a maturity of three months or less at the date of
purchase to be cash equivalents. &nbsp;The fair value of these investments will approximate their carrying value. &nbsp;In general, investments with
original maturities of greater than three months and remaining maturities of less than one year will be classified as short-term investments.
&nbsp;Investments with maturities beyond one year may be classified as short-term based on their highly liquid nature and because such marketable
securities represent the investment of cash that is available for current operations. &nbsp;All cash equivalents and short-term investments are
classified as available for current operations. &nbsp;All cash equivalents and short-term investments are classified as available for sale and are
recorded at market value using the specific identification method.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><I>Fair Value </I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The carrying amounts of cash and cash equivalents, trade receivables, accounts payable, notes payable and accrued
liabilities approximate fair value because of the short maturity of these instruments.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px">Financial Statement Presentation</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px">We have reclassified certain prior-year amounts to conform to the current year presentation.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center>F-7<BR>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><B>COUPON EXPRESS, INC.</B></P>
<P style="margin-top:6.667px; margin-bottom:0px" align=center><B>NOTES&nbsp;TO FINANCIAL STATEMENTS</B></P>
<P style="margin-top:6.667px; margin-bottom:0px" align=center><B>FOR THE YEARS ENDED OCTOBER 31, 2011 AND 2010</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Summary of Significant Accounting Policies (continued)</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><I><U>Loss per Common Share</U></I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><I>&nbsp;&nbsp;</I>&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The Company complies with the accounting and disclosure requirements of FASB ASC 260, &#8220;Earnings Per
Share.&#8221; Basic loss per common share is computed by dividing net loss available to common stockholders by the weighted average number of common
shares outstanding during the period. &nbsp;The calculation of diluted net loss per share excludes 142,107,075 and 59,710,021 warrants and 103,000,000
and 4,000,000 of common stock issuable upon the exercise of options as of October 31, 2011 and 2010 respectively, since their effect is anti-dilutive.
</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><I>Income Taxes</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>We account for income taxes in accordance with FASB ASC Topic 740 &#8220;Income Taxes,&#8221; which requires
accounting for deferred income taxes under the asset and liability method. &nbsp;Deferred income tax asset and liabilities are computed for difference
between the financial statement and tax bases of assets and liabilities that will result in taxable or deductible amounts in the future based on the
enacted tax laws and rates applicable to the periods in which the differences are expected to affect taxable income. &nbsp;Valuation allowances are
established, when necessary, to reduce the deferred income tax assets to the amount expected to be realized.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>In accordance with GAAP, we are required to determine whether our tax position is more
likely than not to be sustained upon examination by the applicable taxing authority, including resolution of any related appeals or litigation
processes, based on the technical merits of the position. We file an income tax return in the U.S. federal jurisdiction, and may file income tax returns
in various U.S. state and local jurisdictions.&nbsp; The tax benefit to be recognized is measured as the largest amount of benefit that is greater than
fifty percent likely of being realized upon ultimate settlement. &nbsp;De-recognition of a tax benefit previously recognized could result in us
recording a tax liability that would reduce net assets. This policy also provides guidance on thresholds, measurement, de-recognition, classification,
interest and penalties, accounting in interim periods, disclosure, and transition that is intended to provide better financial statement comparability
among different entities. &nbsp;It must be applied to all existing tax positions upon initial adoption and the cumulative effect, if any, is to be
reported as an adjustment to stockholder&#8217;s equity as of November 1, 2010. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Based on our analysis, we have determined that the adoption of this policy did not have a
material impact on our financial statements upon adoption. However, management&#8217;s conclusions regarding this policy may be subject to review and
adjustment at a later date based on factors including, but not limited to, on-going analyses of and changes to tax laws, regulations and interpretations
thereof.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><I>Interest and Penalty Recognition on Unrecognized Tax Benefits</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>We recognize interest accrued related to unrecognized tax benefits in interest expense and penalties in operating
expenses. No interest expense or penalties have been recognized for the year ended October 31, 2011.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><I>Comprehensive Income </I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>We comply with FASB ASC Topic 220, &#8220;Comprehensive Income,&#8221; which establishes rules for the reporting and
display of comprehensive income (loss) and its components. &nbsp;FASB ASC Topic 220 requires us to reflect as a separate component of
stockholders&#8217; equity items of comprehensive income.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center>F-8</P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><B>COUPON EXPRESS, INC.</B></P>
<P style="margin-top:6.667px; margin-bottom:0px" align=center><B>NOTES&nbsp;TO FINANCIAL STATEMENTS</B></P>
<P style="margin-top:6.667px; margin-bottom:0px" align=center><B>FOR THE YEARS ENDED OCTOBER 31, 2011 AND 2010</B></P>
<P style="margin-top:6.667px; margin-bottom:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Summary of Significant Accounting Policies (continued)</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-right:20.4px" align=justify><I>Stock-Based Compensation</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>We comply with FASB ASC Topic 718 &#8220;Compensation &#8211; Stock Compensation,&#8221; which establishes standards
for the accounting for transactions in which an entity exchanges its equity instruments for goods or services. &nbsp;It also addresses transactions in
which an entity incurs liabilities in exchange for goods or services that are based on the fair value of the entity&#8217;s equity instruments or that
may be settled by the issuance of those equity instruments. FASB ASC Topic 718 focuses primarily on accounting for transactions in which an entity
obtains employee services in share-based payment transactions. &nbsp;FASB ASC Topic 718 requires an entity to measure the cost of employee services
received in exchange for an award of equity instruments based on the grant-date fair value of the award (with limited exceptions). &nbsp;That cost will
be recognized over the period during which an employee is required to provide service in exchange for the award the requisite service period (usually the vesting period). No compensation costs are recognized
for equity instruments for which employees do not render the requisite service. &nbsp;The grant-date fair value of employee share options and similar
instruments will be estimated using option-pricing models adjusted for the unique characteristics of those instruments (unless observable market prices
for the same or similar instruments are available). &nbsp;If an equity award is modified after the grant date, incremental compensation cost will be
recognized in an amount equal to the excess of the fair value of the modified award over the fair value of the original award immediately before the
modification. For the years ended October 31, 2011 and October, 31, 2010, we issued 3,014,928 and 7,271,401 shares respectively of our $.01 par value
common stock to consultants for consulting services, and in connection with issuance of these shares, for the years ended October 31, 2011 and October
31, 2010 we recorded additional compensation expense of $82,988 and $363,570<B> </B>respectively<B> </B>under FASB ASC 718.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><I>Valuation of Investments in Securities at Fair Value&#8212;Definition and Hierarchy</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>FASB ASC Topic 820 &#8220;Fair Value Measurements and Disclosures&#8221; provides a framework for measuring fair
value under generally accepted accounting principles in the United States and requires expanded disclosures regarding fair value
measurements.&nbsp;&nbsp;ASC 820 defines fair value as the exchange price that would be received for an asset or paid to transfer a liability (i.e., the
&#8220;exit price&#8221;) in an orderly transaction between market participants at the measurement date.&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>In determining fair value, we use various valuation approaches. &nbsp;In accordance with GAAP, a fair value
hierarchy for inputs is used in measuring fair value that maximizes the use of observable inputs and minimizes the use of unobservable inputs by
requiring that the most observable inputs be used when available. &nbsp;Observable inputs are those that market participants would use in pricing the
asset or liability based on market data obtained from sources independent of the company. &nbsp;Unobservable inputs reflect our assumptions about the
inputs market participants would use in pricing the asset or liability developed based on the best information available in the circumstances. FASB ASC
Topic 820 establishes a three-tiered fair value hierarchy that prioritizes inputs to valuation techniques used in fair value calculations, as follows:
</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:24px" align=justify><I>Level 1</I> - Valuations based on unadjusted quoted prices in active markets for identical
assets or liabilities that we have the ability to access. &nbsp;Valuation adjustments and block discounts are not applied to Level 1 securities.
&nbsp;Since valuations are based on quoted prices that are readily and regularly available in an active market, valuation of these securities does not
entail a significant degree of judgment.</P>
<P style="margin-top:5.533px; margin-bottom:5.533px; padding-left:24px" align=justify><I>Level 2</I> - Valuations based on quoted prices in markets that
are not active or for which all significant inputs are observable, either directly or indirectly.</P>
<P style="margin-top:5.533px; margin-bottom:5.533px; padding-left:24px"><I>Level 3 - </I>Valuations based on inputs that are unobservable and
significant to the overall fair value measurement.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The availability of valuation techniques and observable inputs can vary from security
to security and is affected by a wide variety of factors including, the type of security, whether the security is new and not yet established in the
marketplace, and other characteristics particular to the transaction. &nbsp;To the extent that valuation is based on models or inputs that are less
observable or unobservable in the market, the determination of fair value requires more judgment. &nbsp;Those estimated values do not necessarily
represent the amounts that may be ultimately realized due to the occurrence of future circumstances that cannot be reasonably determined. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center>F-9</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>


<!-- *************************************************************************** -->
<!-- MARKER PAGE="sheet: 3; page: 3" -->
<HR SIZE=5 COLOR=GRAY NOSHADE>
<PAGE>

<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><B>COUPON EXPRESS, INC.</B></P>
<P style="margin-top:6.667px; margin-bottom:0px" align=center><B>NOTES&nbsp;TO FINANCIAL STATEMENTS</B></P>
<P style="margin-top:6.667px; margin-bottom:0px" align=center><B>FOR THE YEARS ENDED OCTOBER 31, 2011 AND 2010</B></P>
<P style="margin-top:6.667px; margin-bottom:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Summary of Significant Accounting Policies (continued)</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><I>Valuation of Investments in Securities at Fair Value&#8212;Definition and Hierarchy (continued)</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Because of the inherent uncertainty of valuation, those estimated values may be
materially higher or lower than the values that would have been used had a ready market for the securities existed. Accordingly, the degree of judgment
we exercise in determining fair value is greatest for securities categorized in Level 3. In certain cases, the inputs used to measure fair value may
fall into different&nbsp;levels of the fair value hierarchy. In such&nbsp;cases, for disclosure purposes, the level in the fair value hierarchy within
which the fair value measurement in its entirety falls is determined based on the lowest level input that is significant to the fair value measurement.
</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Fair value is a market-based measure considered from the perspective of a market participant rather than an
entity-specific measure. &nbsp;Therefore, even when market assumptions are not readily available, our own assumptions are set to reflect those that
market participants would use in pricing the asset or liability at the measurement date. &nbsp;We use prices and inputs that are current as of the
measurement date, including periods of market dislocation. &nbsp;In periods of market dislocation, the observability of prices and inputs may be reduced
for many securities. &nbsp;This condition could cause a security to be reclassified to a lower level within the fair value hierarchy. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Valuation Techniques</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>We value investments in securities that are freely tradable and are listed on a national securities exchange or
reported on the NASDAQ national market at their last sales price as of the last business day of the year. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Government Bonds</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The fair value of sovereign government bonds is generally based on quoted prices in active markets. When quoted
prices are not available, fair value is determined based on a valuation model that uses inputs that include interest-rate yield curves,
cross-currency-basis index spreads, and country credit spreads similar to the bond in terms of issuer, maturity and seniority. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Certificate of Deposits </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The fair values of the bank certificate of deposits are based on the face value of the certificate of deposits.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><I>&nbsp;</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Product Warranty &nbsp;</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>We provide for the estimated costs of hardware and software warranties at the time the related revenue is
recognized. &nbsp;For hardware warranty, we estimate the costs based on historical and projected project failure rates, historical and projected repair
costs, and knowledge of specific product failures (if any). &nbsp;The specific hardware warranty terms and conditions vary depending upon the product
supported and country in which we will do business, but generally include technical support, parts, and labor over a period generally ranging from 90
days to three years. &nbsp;For software, we estimate the costs to provide bug fixes, such as security patches, over the estimated life of the software.
&nbsp;We will regularly reevaluate its estimates to assess the adequacy of the recorded warranty liabilities and adjust the amounts as necessary.
Product warranty costs have not been material to date. We have contracted with Speedwire at a flat rate of $50.00 per kiosk per month but service has
not begun as we have not encountered in-field failures. </P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:352.4px" align=justify>F-10</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>

<!-- *************************************************************************** -->
<!-- MARKER PAGE="sheet: 3; page: 3" -->
<HR SIZE=5 COLOR=GRAY NOSHADE>
<PAGE>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><B>COUPON EXPRESS, INC.</B></P>
<P style="margin-top:6.667px; margin-bottom:0px" align=center><B>NOTES&nbsp;TO FINANCIAL STATEMENTS</B></P>
<P style="margin-top:6.667px; margin-bottom:0px" align=center><B>FOR THE YEARS ENDED OCTOBER 31, 2011 AND 2010</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Summary of Significant Accounting Policies (continued)</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Property and Equipment</B> </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Property and equipment is stated at cost less depreciation. &nbsp;Depreciation is computed &nbsp;using the
straight-line method over the estimated life of the asset of 5 years. &nbsp;Repairs and maintenance are expensed as incurred, while betterments and
improvements are capitalized.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Long-Lived Assets</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>In accordance with FASB ASC Topic 360 &#8220;Property, Plant, and Equipment,&#8221; we record impairment losses on
long-lived assets used in operations when indicators of impairment are present and the undiscounted cash flows estimated to be generated by those assets
are less than the assets&#8217; carrying amounts. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Fair Value of Financial Instruments </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The fair values of our assets and liabilities that qualify as financial instruments under FASB ASC Topic 825,
&#8220;Financial Instruments,&#8221; approximate their carrying amounts presented in the accompanying balance sheets at October 31, 2011 and 2010.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Revenue Recognition &nbsp;</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Revenue is recognized when persuasive evidence of an arrangement exists, delivery has occurred, the fee is fixed or
determinable, and collectability is probable. &nbsp;In the event we should enter into contracts where it is obligated to deliver multiple products
and/or services, total revenue will be generally allocated among the products based upon the sale price of each product when sold separately.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>We may also license or lease its products (rather than effect outright sales of the same). &nbsp;Revenues derived
from licenses or leases will be treated as subscriptions, with billings recorded as unearned revenue and recognized as revenue ratably over the billing
coverage period. &nbsp;Our potential multiple year licensing/lease transactions may include the right to receive future updated improvements to its
product line. &nbsp;Some multi-year licensing/lease arrangements may include a perpetual license for current products combined with rights to receive
future improved/updated versions of such products. &nbsp;Online advertising revenue derived from the kiosks and signage
will be recognized as advertisements as they are displayed. &nbsp;Costs related to our product line are recognized
when the related revenue is recognized. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Advertising</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>We expense all advertising expenditures as incurred. &nbsp;Our advertising expenses were $ 0 and $26,345 for the
years ended October 31, 2011 and 2010, respectively.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Use of Estimates</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-right:20.4px" align=justify>The preparation of financial statements in conformity with generally accepted accounting
principles requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect certain reported amounts of assets and liabilities at the date of the
financial statements, as well as their related disclosures. &nbsp;Such estimates and assumptions also affect the reported amounts of revenues and
expenses during the reporting period. &nbsp;Actual results could significantly differ from those estimates.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Recently Adopted Accounting Pronouncements</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>In April 2010, the FASB issued ASU No. 2010-13, &#8220;Compensation - Stock Compensation (Topic 718): Effect of
Denominating the Exercise Price of a Share-Based Payment Award in the Currency of the Market in Which the Underlying Equity Security Trades,&#8221;
which addresses the classification of a share-based payment award with an exercise price denominated in the currency
of a market in</P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:0px" align=center>F-11</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>

<!-- *************************************************************************** -->
<!-- MARKER PAGE="sheet: 3; page: 3" -->
<HR SIZE=5 COLOR=GRAY NOSHADE>
<PAGE>

<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><B>COUPON EXPRESS, INC.</B></P>
<P style="margin-top:6.667px; margin-bottom:0px" align=center><B>NOTES&nbsp;TO FINANCIAL STATEMENTS</B></P>
<P style="margin-top:6.667px; margin-bottom:0px" align=center><B>FOR THE YEARS ENDED OCTOBER 31, 2011 AND 2010</B></P>
<P style="margin-top:6.667px; margin-bottom:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:6.667px; margin-bottom:0px" align=justify><B>Recently Adopted Accounting Pronouncements (continued)</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>which the underlying equity security trades. Topic 718 is amended to clarify that a
share-based payment award with an exercise price denominated in the currency of a market in which a substantial portion of the entity&#8217;s equity securities
trades shall not be considered to contain a market, performance, or service condition. Therefore, such an award is not to be classified as a liability
if it otherwise qualifies as equity classification. The amendments in this update should be applied by recording a cumulative-effect adjustment to the
opening balance of retained earnings. The cumulative-effect adjustment should be calculated for all awards outstanding as of the beginning of the fiscal
year in which the amendments are initially applied, as if the amendments had been applied consistently since the inception of the award. ASU No. 2010-13
is effective for interim and annual periods beginning on or after December 15, 2010 and is not expected to have a material impact on the Company&#8217;s
consolidated financial position or results of operations. The Company adopted the pronouncement on January 1, 2011 resulting in no impact to the
Company&#8217;s financial statements.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>On June 16, 2011, the FASB issued ASU No. 2011-05, &#8220;Presentation of
Comprehensive Income (Topic 220),&#8221; which requires companies to report total net income, each component of comprehensive income, and total
comprehensive income on the face of the income statement, or as two consecutive statements. The components of comprehensive income will not be changed,
nor does the ASU affect how earnings per share is calculated or reported. These amendments will be reported retrospectively upon adoption. The adoption
of the ASU will be required for the Company&#8217;s January 31, 2012 Form 10-Q filing, and is not expected to have a material impact on the Company.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>In December 2010, FASB issued ASC ASU 2010-28, &#8220;When to Perform Step 2 of the
Goodwill Impairment Test for Reporting Units with Zero or Negative Carrying Amounts (Topic 350) &#8212; Intangibles &#8212; Goodwill and Other.&#8221;
ASU 2010-28 amends the criteria for performing Step 2 of the goodwill impairment test for reporting units with zero or negative carrying amounts and
requires performing Step 2, if qualitative factors indicate that it is more likely than not that goodwill impairment exists. Any impairment to be
recorded upon adoption will be recognized as an adjustment to our beginning retained earnings. The Company adopted the pronouncement on January 1, 2011
resulting in no impact to the Company&#8217;s financial statements.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>In January 2010, the FASB issued Accounting Standards Update 2010-06,<I> </I>&#8220;Fair Value Measurements and
Disclosures (Topic 820) - Improving Disclosures about Fair Value Measurements&#8221; (ASU 2010-06), to require new disclosures related to transfers into
and out of Levels 1 and 2 of the fair value hierarchy and additional disclosure requirements related to Level 3 measurements. &nbsp;The guidance also
clarifies existing fair value measurement disclosures about the level of disaggregation and about inputs and valuation techniques used to measure fair
value. &nbsp;The additional disclosure requirements are effective for the first reporting period beginning after December 15, 2009, except for the
additional disclosure requirements related to Level 3 measurements, which are effective for fiscal years beginning after December 15, 2010. &nbsp;The
adoption of the additional requirements is not expected to have any financial impact on our financial statements.</P>

<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; padding-left:0px; text-indent:0px"><B>4. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Debt;</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><I>Bridge Loans</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>In February and March 2007, we entered into notes (&#8220;Bridge Notes&#8221;) with several unrelated parties
totaling approximately $325,000.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Bridge Notes were originally due on November 11, 2009 and incurred an interest rate of 12% per annum.
</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>In August 2007, we entered into exchange agreements with the holders of $300,000 of the Bridge Notes, wherein the
notes were to be converted into 3,000,000 shares of our common stock.&nbsp;&nbsp;We originally expected these notes to be converted into common stock
shares during the first or second quarter of the fiscal year ending October 31, 2011. One of the note holders converted his $25,000 note into 208,333
shares of common stock in December 2008.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>In May and June of 2008, we entered into a new series of Bridge Notes with several unrelated parties totaling
$470,000. &nbsp;The Bridge Notes were originally due six months from the date of issuance and incur interest at the rate of 10% per annum. &nbsp;On July
2, 2010, the Bridge Note was amended to extend the due date to December 1, 2010. The notes are convertible by the holder at any time at a  conversion price
 equal to the per share price of a new issuance. In connection with the Bridge Notes, we also issued
warrants to purchase 470,000 shares of our common stock at an exercise price $.15 and warrants to purchase 470,000 shares of our common stock at an
exercise price of $.25, reduced to $.05 and $.15, respectively, by the July 2, 2010 Amendment to the Bridge Notes.&nbsp;&nbsp;The warrants may be
exercisable at any time for a period of 5 years.&nbsp;&nbsp;In connection with the issuance of the warrants, we reflected a value for the warrants
totaling $47,112; no value adjustment was reflected for the price reduction, as the value change was not material.&nbsp;The fair value of the warrant
grant was estimated on the date of the grant using the Black-Scholes option-pricing model with the following weighted average assumptions: expected
volatility of 15%, risk free interest rate of 4.86%; and expected lives of 5 years. On </P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><I>Round D Loans</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><I>&nbsp;&nbsp;</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Commencing May through October 2007, we entered into notes (&#8220;Round D Notes&#8221;) with several unrelated
parties totaling approximately $2,916,000.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Round D Notes incur interest at rates ranging from 12% to 14% per annum, payable semi-annually
and are due 3 years from the date of issuance.&nbsp;&nbsp;These notes were not paid by October 31, 2010.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>In connection with the Round D Notes, we also issued warrants to purchase 9,445,744 shares of our common stock at an
exercise price of $.15.&nbsp;&nbsp;The warrants may be exercisable at any time for a period of 5 years.&nbsp;&nbsp;In connection with the issuance of
the warrants, we have reflected a value for the warrants totalling $549,011.&nbsp;&nbsp;The fair value of the warrant grant was estimated on the date of
the grant using the Black-Scholes option-pricing model with the following weighted average assumptions: expected volatility of 15%, risk free interest
rate of 3.57%; and expected lives of 5 years. For the years ending October 31, 2011 and 2010 the company issued 48,372,496 and 13,606,592 shares of
common stock respectively in payment of accrued interest and principal. &nbsp;In addition, note holders of $646,000 of the remaining $711,000
outstanding convertible notes, have agreed to extend the due dates of their notes until October 2012 and also to subordinate their notes to the new
Senior Convertible Notes. In November 2011 $50,000 was repaid to one of the outstanding note holders.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><I>Round E Loans</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>In April, July and August 2009, we entered into a series of convertible notes aggregating $170,000. The notes are
due one year from the date of issuance and incur interest at the rate of 10% per annum.&nbsp; In connection with the notes, we issued five year warrants
to purchase 1,602,857 shares of our common stock at an exercise price of $.05 per share. The warrants may be exercisable at any time for a period of 5
years.&nbsp;&nbsp;No expense was recorded for these warrants as the additional cost was not material. &nbsp;The notes were not paid by the due date;
however, the note holders waived the default. In October 2011 the company issued 4,230,240 shares
in payment of all outstanding accrued interest and principal owed the note holders for this Round.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>In March 2009, we obtained interest free advances from two of its officers totaling $40,000. In November 2011 one of
these loans totaling $20,000 was repaid. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><I>Round F Loans</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>In November 2009, January 2010 and March 2010, we entered into a series of convertible notes aggregating $419,000.
The notes were originally due one year from the date of issuance at an interest rate of 10% per annum.&nbsp;In connection with the notes, we issued five
year warrants to purchase 11,971,429 shares of our common stock at an exercise price of $.05 per share. The warrants may be exercisable at any time over
&nbsp;period of 5 years.&nbsp;&nbsp;In connection with the issuance of the warrants and conversion features, the Company has reflected a value totaling
$236,417.&nbsp;&nbsp;The fair value of the warrant grant was estimated on the date of the grant using the Black Scholes option-pricing model with the
following weighted average assumptions: expected volatility of 15%, risk free interest rate of 2.068 to 2.60% and expected lives of 5 years. &nbsp;In
October 2011 the company issued 12,641,938 shares in payment of all accrued interest and principal owed for this Round.</P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><I>Cumulative Convertible Senior Notes</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>In October 2011, we completed a private placement of $1,462,500 aggregate principal amount of Cumulative Convertible
Senior Notes (&#8220;Senior Notes&#8221;) and Warrants to certain investors, that included the Company&#8217;s existing Series A Preferred Stockholders.
&nbsp;The Senior Notes, which mature on October 24, 2012 (subject to a one-year extension under certain circumstances), are convertible into shares of
the Company&#8217;s Series A Preferred Stock (&#8220;Preferred Stock&#8221;) at a rate of one share of Preferred Stock for each $25,000 of Senior Notes.
&nbsp;Upon the conversion of the Company&#8217;s remaining convertible debt, or upon the consent of a majority in principal amount of the Senior Notes,
the Senior Notes will be converted into shares of Preferred Stock. &nbsp;The Senior Notes are secured obligations of Coupon Express and will bear
interest at a rate of 7% per year.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The shares of Preferred Stock bear a cumulative dividend of 7% per annum. &nbsp;Upon liquidation, and upon an
acquisition of the Company, the holders of Preferred Stock are entitled to a liquidation preference equal to the greater of (i) the amount invested plus
all accrued and unpaid dividends, or the amount the holders of Preferred Stock would receive had they converted the Preferred Stock to Common Stock
immediately prior to such event. &nbsp;Each share of Preferred Stock is convertible into 1,250,000 shares of the Company&#8217;s Common Stock, subject
to certain adjustments. &nbsp;The Certificate of Designation of the Preferred Stock provides that without the consent of a majority of the outstanding
principal amount of Notes (or Series A Preferred Stock, if converted), the Company may not:</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px">1.</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px">amend the Articles of Incorporation, by-laws, Certificate of Designation or any other certificate of
designation or file any new certificate of designation;</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px">2.</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px">issue any Common Stock, Preferred Stock, Common Stock Equivalents or other securities or amend the terms
thereof;</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px">3.</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px">redeem any outstanding Common Stock, Preferred Stock, Common Stock Equivalents or other securities;</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px">4.</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px">incur or repay indebtedness for borrowed money;</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px">5.</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px">acquisitions or dispositions of material assets;</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px">6.</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px">enter into any acquisition, merger, consolidation, reorganization or similar transaction;</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px">7.</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px">create subsidiaries or other affiliates;</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px">8.</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px">dissolve, liquidate or wind up or file any petition under insolvency or bankruptcy laws;</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-24px">9.</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px">enter into any contract or arrangement with any present or former director, executive officer, shareholder,
partner, member, employee or affiliate of the Company or any of its subsidiaries, or any of such Person's affiliates or immediate family members;</P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The Warrants are exercisable until October 24, 2016 at a price of $.04 per share (subject to certain adjustments)
and entitle the holder to purchase 1,250,000 shares of the Company&#8217;s Common Stock for each $25,000 of principal amount of Senior Notes. &nbsp;The
investors have entered into an Investors&#8217; Rights Agreement which among other things, provides for Board representation, registration rights, and
certain provisions regarding future sales of securities by the Company.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>In prior rounds of financing, the Company issued certain warrants, rights convertible into or exercisable or
exchangeable for common stock (collectively the &quot;Derivative Securities&quot;).&nbsp; The Derivative Securities contain certain anti-dilution
provisions, which provide for adjustment of the conversion price, exercise price or number of shares issuable, upon the occurrence of certain events.
The Purchase Agreement required the Company, within 90 days of the closing date,&nbsp;to obtain from the holders of the Derivative Securities, a waiver,
except in the case of any capital reorganization, split, combination or subdivision or reclassification, of any anti-dilution adjustments, it may have
with respect to the Derivative Securities.&nbsp;In the event the Company is unable to obtain waivers from all of the holders of the Derivative
Securities, the investors under&nbsp;the terms of the Purchase Agreement will be entitled to an adjustment of the conversion price, exercise price and
the number of shares of common stock issuable to them under the Purchase Agreement<FONT style="font-family:Arial">.</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; padding-left:0px; text-indent:0px"><B>5. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Commitments</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><I>Operating Leases</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><I>Real Estate</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>In our Colorado Springs office, we currently lease office space and equipment under a non-cancellable operating
lease agreement that expires in November 2011. Our New York headquarters lease is month to month. The total rent expense for these operating leases were
approximately $30,918 and $61,927 for the years ended October 31, 2010 and 2009, respectively.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><I>Equipment</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>In June 2011 the Company entered into a Master Leasing Agreement with Yellow Box Leasing LLC. &nbsp;The terms of the
agreement provide up to $1.25 million in equipment lease financing for Coupon Express Kiosks. The lease provides for the creation of sub-leases for each
order of 25 Kiosks ordered. In September 2011 the Company received 25 new Kiosks with a value of $ 125,000. &nbsp;&nbsp;Terms of this sub-lease provide
for payments of $140/month for each Kiosk over 3 years.</P>

<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><I>Legal</I></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The Company is involved in a dispute over a services contract. &nbsp;S.O.S. Resources (&#8220;SOS&#8221;) and its
president claim that SOS fully performed under an agreement with the Company and is entitled to receive 3,110,000 shares of our registered common stock,
and later asserted that they would seek a sum of $1,191,600 from the Company. &nbsp;The Company believes that SOS and its president did not perform
under the contract, and intends to vigorously defend itself against such claim as well as file a claim for fraud against SOS and its president.
&nbsp;The Company believes that the suit filed by SOS and its president is without merit; however, we will have to pay costs associated with arbitrating
this claim.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; padding-left:0px; text-indent:0px"><B>6. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Income Taxes</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>We have not filed federal or state tax returns for the years ended October 31, 2004 - 2010. &nbsp;We did not believe
that we owed material federal or state taxes for these fiscal years as a result of our operating losses. At October 31, 2011, we had approximately $19.8
million of net operating losses (&#8220;NOL&#8221;) carryforwards for federal and state income purposes. &nbsp;These losses are available for future
years and expire through 2031. Utilization of these losses may be severely or completely limited if we undergo an ownership change pursuant to Internal
Revenue Code Section 382.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px">The deferred tax asset is summarized as follows: </P>

<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; text-indent:60px">Inventory reserved</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; text-indent:333.333px"><U>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;0</U></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:479px"><U>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;96,120</U></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; text-indent:333.333px">&nbsp;$6,738,000</P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:480px">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;5,423,791</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; text-indent:60px">Valuation allowance</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; text-indent:333.333px"><U>&nbsp;&nbsp;(6,738,000</U>)</U></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:477.733px"><U>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;(5,423,791</U>)</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; text-indent:60px">Net deferred income tax asset</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-12px; text-indent:333.333px"><U>$&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</U></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-18px; text-indent:333.333px"><U>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</U></P>

<P style="margin:0px; margin-bottom:-12px; text-indent:480px"><U>$&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;-&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</U></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:480px"><U>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</U></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Generally accepted accounting principles requires that the tax benefit of net operating losses, temporary
differences and credit carryforwards be recorded as an asset to the extent that management assesses that realization is &#8220;more likely than
not.&#8221; Realization of the future tax benefits is dependent on the Company's ability to generate sufficient taxable income within the carryforward
period. Because of our history of operating losses, management has provided a valuation allowance equal to its net deferred tax assets.</P>
<P style="margin:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; padding-left:0px; text-indent:0px"><B>7. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Prior Period Adjustment </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px">For the year ended October 31, 2010, we identified approximately $1.642 million of errors relating to an overstatement primarily
of accounts payable, accrued expenses and other balance sheet items from the year ended October 31, 2009; $1.144 million was disclosed in the quarter
ended July 31, 2010. &nbsp;Accordingly, the balance sheet for October 31, 2010 presented in this Form 10-K has </P>


<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center>F-17</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>

<!-- *************************************************************************** -->
<!-- MARKER PAGE="sheet: 3; page: 3" -->
<HR SIZE=5 COLOR=GRAY NOSHADE>
<PAGE>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=center><B>COUPON EXPRESS, INC.</B></P>
<P style="margin-top:6.667px; margin-bottom:0px" align=center><B>NOTES&nbsp;TO FINANCIAL STATEMENTS</B></P>
<P style="margin-top:6.667px; margin-bottom:0px" align=center><B>FOR THE YEARS ENDED OCTOBER 31, 2011 AND 2010</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><B>7. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Prior Period Adjustment (continued) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px">been adjusted to reduce accounts payable , accrued &nbsp;expenses and other balance sheet &nbsp;accounts by the $1.642 million; a
corresponding entry was recorded to reduce previously reported accumulated deficit by the same amount.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-16px; padding-left:24px; text-indent:-24px"><B>8. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Subsequent Events </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px">Subsequent to October 31, 2011, the company made cash payments of $202,716 in satisfaction of principal and interest owed for
certain note holders in Rounds D, G and Bridge and also the company purchased additional Kiosks for $155,000.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px">Management had evaluated subsequent events through January 16, 2012, the date of which the financial statements were available to
be issued.</P>

present in all material respects the financial condition, results of operations and cash flows of the registrant as of, and for, the periods presented

Act Rules 13a-15(f) and 15d-15(f)) for the registrant and have:</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>(a) Designed such disclosure controls and procedures, or caused such disclosure controls and procedures to be
designed under our supervision, to ensure that material information relating to the registrant, including its consolidated subsidiaries, is made known
to us by others within those entities, particularly during the period in which this report is being prepared;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>(b) Designed such internal control over financial reporting, or caused such internal control over financial
reporting to be designed under our supervision, to provide reasonable assurance regarding the reliability of financial reporting and the preparation of
financial statements for external purposes in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>(c) Evaluated the effectiveness of the registrant&#8217;s disclosure controls and procedures and presented in this

occurred during the registrant&#8217;s most recent fiscal quarter (the registrant&#8217;s fourth fiscal quarter in the case of an annual report) that
has materially affected, or is reasonably likely to materially affect, the registrant&#8217;s internal control over financial reporting; and</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>

the registrant&#8217;s internal control over financial reporting.</P>

	&lt;p style="margin: 0px; padding-left: 24px;"&gt;&lt;b&gt;Fixed Assets&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p align="justify" style="margin: 0px;"&gt;&lt;br/&gt;
	&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p align="justify" style="margin: 0px;"&gt;&lt;font style="background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);"&gt;Furniture and equipment consist of the following:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p align="justify" style="margin: 0px;"&gt;&lt;br/&gt;
	&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: -16px; text-indent: 355px;"&gt;&lt;u&gt;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;October 31,&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p style="margin-top: 0px; text-indent: 480px;"&gt;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: -16px; text-indent: 344px;"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&lt;u&gt;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;2011&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p style="margin-top: 0px; text-indent: 482px;"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;u&gt;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;2010&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p style="margin-top: 0px; text-indent: 60px;"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;u&gt;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Description&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: -16px; text-indent: 60px;"&gt;Kiosks&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: -16px; text-indent: 333.333px;"&gt;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;$ 375,612&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: -16px; text-indent: 480px;"&gt;$&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;258,850&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p style="margin-top: 0px;"&gt;&lt;br/&gt;
	&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: -16px; text-indent: 60px;"&gt;Less: &amp;#160;accumulated depreciation&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: -16px; text-indent: 355.333px;"&gt;&lt;u&gt;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;123,105&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p style="margin-top: 0px; text-indent: 480px;"&gt;&lt;u&gt;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;25,885&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: -12px; text-indent: 357px;"&gt;&lt;u&gt;$ 252,507&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: -18px; text-indent: 357px;"&gt;&lt;u&gt;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: -12px; text-indent: 480px;"&gt;&lt;u&gt;$&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;232,965&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: -16px; text-indent: 480px;"&gt;&lt;u&gt;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

	&lt;p align="left" style="margin-left: 60px;"&gt;Depreciation expense for the year ended October 31, 2011 and 2010 totaled $ 97,221 and $25,885, respectively.&lt;/p&gt;
